05148nam a2200637Ia 9780226586571DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226586571  a(DE-B1597)642290  a(OCoLC)1351747437  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBJ1535 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a179/.8qOCoLC223/eng/202301201 aSchneider, Robert A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Return of Resentment :bThe Rise and Decline and Rise Again of a Political Emotion /cRobert A. Schneider. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Life of Ideas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1: Sensible Resentment in the Age of Sensibility: The Eighteenth Century -- t2: Contentious Resentment: Acting Out Resentment in the Early Modern Past -- t3: A Specter Is Haunting Europe: The Specter of a Resentful “People” -- t4: The Nietzschean Moment -- t5: The Rise and Decline of the “Resentment Paradigm” -- t6: The Uses of Resentment -- t7: The Two Sixties and Resentment: One Without, the Other With -- t8: The Return of Resentment: Anatomizing a Contemporary Political Emotion -- tConclusion: Thinking about Resentment Today -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCharts the long history of resentment, from its emergence to its establishment as the word of the moment. The term “resentment,” often casually paired with words like “hatred,” “rage,” and “fear,” has dominated US news analysis since November 2016. Despite its increased use, this word seems to defy easy categorization. Does “resentment” describe many interlocking sentiments, or is it just another way of saying “anger”? Does it suggest an irrational grievance, as opposed to a legitimate callout of injustice? Does it imply political leanings, or is it nonpartisan by nature? In The Return of Resentment, Robert A. Schneider explores these questions and more, moving from eighteenth-century Britain to the aftermath of the French Revolution to social movements throughout the twentieth century. Drawing on a wide range of writers, thinkers, and historical experiences, Schneider illustrates how resentment has morphed across time, coming to express a collective sentiment felt by people and movements across the political spectrum. In this history, we discover resentment’s modernity and its ambiguity—how it can be used to dismiss legitimate critique and explain away violence, but also convey a moral stance that demands recognition. Schneider anatomizes the many ways resentment has been used to label present-day movements, from followers of Trump and supporters of Brexit to radical Islamicists and proponents of identity politics. Addressing our contemporary political situation in a novel way, The Return of Resentment challenges us to think critically about the roles different emotions play in politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEurope-History. 0aPolitical psychologyzEuropexHistory. 0aResentmentxPolitical aspectszEurope. 0aResentmentxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aResentmentzEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aresentment, Donald Trump, Brexit, Friedrich Nietzsche, Populism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eB